			<td bgcolor="#ffffff" valign="top" class="twikiTableCol1 twikiLast"> <code>root</code> </td>
			<td bgcolor="#ffffff" valign="top" class="twikiTableCol2 twikiLastCol twikiLast"> <code>/etc/grid-security/hostcert.pem</code> <br> <code>/etc/grid-security/hostkey.pem</code> </td>
		</tr></table>
</td>
</tr>
<tr class="twikinetWrapperTableRow">
<td class="twikinetWrapperTableB twikinetWrapperTableBL"></td>
<td class="twikinetWrapperTableB twikinetWrapperTableBR"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p />
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  GUMS versions 1.3.18 or later can work without a host cert or proxy.  To do this, <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/GlexecPilotCert" class="twikiLink">follow these directions</a>.  The directions below only apply to older GUMS installs.
</dd></dl> 
<p />
A host certificate on every worker node is required for glexec to use GUMS.  The host certificates do not need to be unique on every node; you can share the same one for every node in the cluster.  If you don't have any host certificate for the worker nodes, or you want to avoid the risk of a shared certificate getting stolen, you can use limited-duration proxies instead.  There is a host proxy distribution script package called <a href="https://twiki.grid.iu.edu/twiki/pub/Documentation/Release3/InstallGlexec/host_dist_latest.tgz" target="_top">host_dist_latest.tgz</a> which can be installed on your gatekeeper and which will automatically create a proxy from your gatekeeper's host certificate and push it out to <code>/etc/grid-security/hostproxy.pem</code> and <code>/etc/grid-security/hostproxykey.pem</code> on your worker nodes.  The script requires a means of passwordless ssh/scp access from the head node to the worker nodes.  The location of the certificate and key can be overridden by setting <code>-cert /etc/grid-security/hostproxy.pem</code> and <code>-key /etc/grid-security/hostproxykey.pem</code> parameters in the gumsclient section of <code>/etc/lcmaps.db</code>.
<p />
Finally, GUMS versions &gt;= 1.3.18 can be configured to not require a certificate or proxy from glexec at all, by changing the "userGroups" tag from access="read self" to access="read all", and by setting the hostToGroup mapping to allow a DN that maps all worker nodes' hostnames. 
<p />
<!-- THIS DOESN'T SEEM TO BE TRUE ANYMORE -- dwd 10/17/12
 ---## Condor Configuration
<p />
If you are using Condor on your worker nodes, you must disable Condor's GSI delegation or glexec won't work. Specifically, you need to set the following in your Condor configuration file. 
<p />
<pre class="file">
DELEGATE_JOB_GSI_CREDENTIALS = FALSE
</pre>
<p />
If this is not done, it can result in glexec getting an error "Verifying certificate chain: proxy path length constraint exceeded" or "lcmaps: Error: grid_verifyPathLenConstraints: Proxy Path Length Constraint exceeded".  This only happens on one type of X509 proxy, however, known variously as pre-RFC, GT3, or version 3.
<p />
<a href="http://research.cs.wisc.edu/condor/manual/v7.6/3_3Configuration.html#param:DelegateJobGSICredentials" target="_top">Condor 7.6 documentation on DELEGATE_JOB_GSI_CREDENTIALS</a>.
